Precision-recall curve is more useful in our case than ROC because our training set is heavily imbalanced. The negative class dominating the positive class in terms of sample size makes ROC difficult to evaluate the performace of a classifier based on the overall accuracy or ROC where True Negative is included. Instead, the precision-recall curve plots precision against recall, focusing more on the effective diagonise of minority class 'Diabetes'. It measures how well the classifier is able to detect positive class (recall) with avoiding false positive (precision.

$$ \text{precision} = \frac{TP}{TP+FP} \quad \text{and} \quad \text{recall} = \frac{TP}{TP+FN} $$

Trade-off can also exists as changing threshold is applied. For example, if I set the threshold extremely close to 0, which means almost every drawn sample will be loaded with '-1', of course it will get classified as 'No diabetes'. Only people with a very high probability of having diabetes are classified as positive. In such case, (assuming our classifer at least classified one positive case), FP will be extremely low because the classifier is very confident about its positive predictors, the precision will be extremely close to 1. However, recall will be low because we simply classify a large proportion of patients as negative which results a high FN rate. Vice versa. Our plot gives the shape we would expect -- at thresholds with low recall, the precision is correspondingly high.

A higher AUC indicates our classifer has overall high recall and high precision in together. We can see the AUC of weight bootstrap is 0.67, much higher than 0.60 of unweighted one. This indicates that weighted bootstrap helps to diagnose as much true positive as possible, meanwhile retain a lower false negative rate. This is desirable in our case because we successfully discover most diabetic patients, minimise the hidden diabetic patients we missed out.

In conclusion, in a very skewed dataset as diabetes_samples, AUC of Precision-Recall Curve is more informative, and indeed weighted bootstrapping gives us a better classifier.

2.2 Support Vector Machine (SVM) (30 marks)¶

2.2.1

In this section, I will train a soft-margin linear SVM classifier by minimising the loss function $$ L = \frac{1}{2} \|\boldsymbol w\|^2 + \lambda \sum_{i=1}^N max\{0, 1-y^{(i)}(\boldsymbol x^{(i)} \cdot \boldsymbol{w} + b)\} $$ to find an optimal hyper-plane $\mathbb{H} := \{ \boldsymbol x: \boldsymbol x \cdot \boldsymbol w + b=0\}$ where parameter $\boldsymbol w \in \mathbb{R}^n$ and normal direction $b \in \mathbb{R}$.

Soft-margin linear SVM is used when the dataset is not possible for perfect hard-margin separation. In other words, we can not find a hyper-plane that separates binary outcomes perfectly. Instead, we allow some points to fall onto the wrong side of the plane. We do this by introducing the penalty term, and the hyper-parameter $\lambda$ serves as a degree of importance that is given to misclassifications. When $\lambda$ tends to 0 (without being 0) the more the miss-classifications are allowed.

As usual, we first set up feature set and target set. One thing to notice is that we also set up an argument matrix for freature set to include the normal dirction $b$. But unlike in section 1, we here add the column vector of ones on the right:

$$ X' = (X|1) $$

Correspondingly $b$ is added to $\mathbf{w}$ as last entry.

def compute_cost(w, X, y, regul_strength=1e5):
    """
    Calculate the cost of the loss function of soft-margin linear SVM.

    :param w: parameter of hyper-plane
    :param X: feature set (include normal direction b)
    :param y: target set (Binary classification in our case)
    :param regul_strength: degree of importance of misclassification

    :return cost: cost of the loss function
    
    """
    n = X.shape[0]
    distances = 1 - y * (X @ w) 
    distances[distances < 0] = 0  # equivalent to max(0, distance)
    hinge = regul_strength * distances.mean() 
        
    # calculate cost
    return 0.5 * np.dot(w, w) + hinge -0.5*w[-1]**2


def calculate_cost_gradient(w, X_batch, y_batch, regul_strength=1e6):
    """
    Calculate the gradient of the cost function of soft-margin linear SVM for a batch of examples.

    :param w: parameter of hyper-plane
    :param X_batch: a batch of feature vectors (include normal direction b)
    :param y_batch: a batch of target values (Binary classification in our case)
    :param regul_strength: degree of importance of misclassification

    :return dw: gradient of the cost function with respect to w
    """
    # if only one example is passed
    if type(y_batch) == np.float64 or type(y_batch) == np.int64:
        y_batch = np.asarray([y_batch])
        X_batch = np.asarray([X_batch])  # gives multidimensional array

    distance = 1 - (y_batch * (X_batch @ w))
    dw = np.zeros(len(w))
    
    we = w.copy() # So as not to overwrite w
    we[-1] = 0 # So as not to have b in its derivative when adding the weights in di
        
    for ind, d in enumerate(distance):
        if max(0, d)==0:
            di = we # derivative of first term
        else:
            di = we - (regul_strength * y_batch[ind] * X_batch[ind])
        dw += di

    return dw/len(y_batch)  # average

def sgd(X, y, max_iterations=2000, stop_criterion=0.01, learning_rate=1e-5, regul_strength=1e6, print_outcome=False):
    """
    Perform stochastic gradient descent to train a soft-margin linear SVM.

    :param X: feature set (include normal direction b)
    :param y: target set (Binary classification in our case)
    :param max_iterations: maximum number of iterations to perform
    :param stop_criterion: minimum relative change in cost for convergence
    :param learning_rate: the step size of each iteration
    :param regul_strength: degree of importance of misclassification
    :param print_outcome: whether to print cost and iteration during training

    :return weights: final weights of the SVM model
    """
    # initialise zero weights
    weights = np.zeros(X.shape[1])
    nth = 0
    # initialise starting cost as infinity
    prev_cost = np.inf
    
    # stochastic gradient descent
    indices = np.arange(len(y))

    for iteration in range(1, max_iterations):
        # shuffle to prevent repeating update cycles
        np.random.shuffle(indices)
        X, y = X[indices], y[indices]
        
        for xi, yi in zip(X, y):
            descent = calculate_cost_gradient(weights, xi, yi, regul_strength) 
            weights = weights - (learning_rate * descent)

        # convergence check on 2^n'th iteration
        if iteration==2**nth or iteration==max_iterations-1:
            # compute cost
            cost = compute_cost(weights, X, y, regul_strength)  
            if print_outcome:
                print("Iteration is: {}, Cost is: {}".format(iteration, cost))
            # stop criterion
            if abs(prev_cost - cost) < stop_criterion * prev_cost:
                return weights
                
            prev_cost = cost
            nth += 1
    
    return weights

def svm_score(w, X_test, y_test, measure):
    """
    Evaluate the performance of a support vector machine (SVM) model on a test set.

    :param w: A numpy array containing the weights of the SVM model.
    :param X_test: A numpy array of shape (n_samples, n_features) containing the test set features.
    :param y_test: A numpy array of shape (n_samples,) containing the test set labels.
    :param measure: A string indicating the evaluation metric to be used. Possible values are 'accuracy', 'precision', 'recall', 'f1', 'auc'.

    :return score: The value of the evaluation metric for the given SVM model on the test set.
    """
    y_pred = np.sign(X_test @ w)
    return rf_score(y_test, y_pred, measure)

def svm_cross_validation_evaluate(X_train1, y_train1, num_folds, regul_strength, measure, max_iteration=5000, stop_criterion=1e-6, learning_rate=1e-5):
    """
    Perform cross-validation on the training set to tune the hyper-parameters and evaluate the performance of the 
    model.

    :param X_train1: feature set of the training set
    :param y_train1: target set of the training set
    :param num_folds: number of folds to be used for cross-validation
    :param regul_strength: degree of importance of misclassification
    :param measure: evaluation metric to be used for scoring
    :param max_iteration: maximum number of iterations for stochastic gradient descent algorithm
    :param stop_criterion: stopping criterion for early termination of training
    :param learning_rate: learning rate for the stochastic gradient descent algorithm
    
    :return: mean of the training scores, mean of the validation scores
    """
    
    def cross_val_split(N, num_folds):
        fold_size = N // num_folds
        #np.random.seed(2)
        index_perm = np.random.permutation(np.arange(N))
        folds = []
        for k in range(num_folds):
            folds.append(index_perm[k*fold_size:(k+1)*fold_size])
        return folds

    folds = cross_val_split(X_train1.shape[0], num_folds)

    train_scores = []
    val_scores = []
    
    for i in range(len(folds)):

        val_indices = folds[i]
        # define the training set
        train_indices = list(set(range(X_train1.shape[0])) - set(val_indices))

        X_train = X_train1[train_indices, :]  
        y_train = y_train1[train_indices]
        
        # define the validation set
        X_val = X_train1[val_indices, :]  
        y_val = y_train1[val_indices]  
        
        # insert 1 in every row for intercept b
        X_train = np.hstack((X_train, np.ones((len(X_train),1)) ))
        X_val = np.hstack((X_val, np.ones((len(X_val),1)) ))  

        # train the model
        w = sgd(X_train, y_train, max_iterations=max_iteration, stop_criterion=stop_criterion, 
                learning_rate=learning_rate, regul_strength=regul_strength)

        # evaluate
        train_score = svm_score(w, X_train, y_train, measure)
        val_score = svm_score(w, X_val, y_val, measure)
    
        train_scores.append(train_score)
        val_scores.append(val_score)

    train_scores_mean = np.mean(np.array(train_scores))
    val_scores_mean = np.mean(np.array(val_scores))

    return train_scores_mean, val_scores_mean

def svm_choose_best_lambda(X_train, y_train, folds, lambda_range, measure, max_iteration=2000, stop_criterion=0.01, learning_rate=1e-3):
    """
    Choose the best regularization parameter (lambda) for a soft-margin SVM using cross-validation.

    Args:
        X_train (ndarray): Training data input features with shape (n_samples, n_features).
        y_train (ndarray): Training data target variable with shape (n_samples,).
        folds (int): Number of folds for cross-validation.
        lambda_range (list): List of regularization parameters to try.
        measure (str): The evaluation metric to use. 'accuracy', 'f1_score', 'precision', or 'recall'.
        max_iteration (int): Maximum number of iterations for the stochastic gradient descent optimization algorithm.
        stop_criterion (float): The stopping criterion for the stochastic gradient descent optimization algorithm.
        learning_rate (float): The learning rate for the stochastic gradient descent optimization algorithm.

    Returns:
        float: The optimal regularization parameter (lambda) that maximizes the validation set accuracy.
    """
    lambda_train_scores = np.zeros(len(lambda_range))
    lambda_val_scores = np.zeros(len(lambda_range))

    #Loop over each lambda
    for i, lambda_ in enumerate(lambda_range):
        #print(lambda_)
        lambda_train_scores[i], lambda_val_scores[i] = svm_cross_validation_evaluate(X_train, y_train, folds, lambda_, 
                                        measure, max_iteration, stop_criterion, learning_rate)
    best_lambda_idx = np.argmax(lambda_val_scores)

    plt.figure(figsize=(15,8))
    plt.plot(lambda_range, lambda_train_scores, color='teal', marker='o', linestyle='-', alpha=0.5, label='Training set accuracy')
    plt.plot(lambda_range, lambda_val_scores, color='orange', marker='o', linestyle='-', label='Validation set accuracy')
    plt.plot(lambda_range[best_lambda_idx], np.max(lambda_val_scores), marker='*', color='red', markersize=15)
    plt.xlabel('Lambda', size=20)
    plt.ylabel('Average Accuracy', size=20)
    plt.title(r"Grid search of $\lambda$ of soft-margin SVM", size=20)
    plt.legend()
    plt.grid()
    plt.show()

    print("-------------------------------------")
    print(f"Optimal hardness hyper-parameter lambda: {lambda_range[best_lambda_idx]}")
    print(f"Resulting maximum accuracy: {np.max(lambda_val_scores)}")
    return lambda_range[best_lambda_idx]

Our reported optimal hardness $\lambda$ is 20, and the average accuracy is approx 0.923.

Optimal SVM wants to increase the distance of decision boundary to classes (or support vectors), and maximize the number of points that are correctly classified in the training set.

For low hardness penalty, $\lambda$ is small, the penalty for misclassified points is low so a decision boundary with a large margin is chosen at the expense of a greater number of misclassifications. The SVM will not be sensitive to new data points added in. The good thing is the SVM will perform equally good and stable on training set and test set, however, large amount of misclassification could result in a low accuracy. This can be comfirmed by first section of the plot: two lines are quite close to each other, but accuracy is not satisfactory.

For high hardness, $\lambda$ is large, SVM tries to minimise the number of misclassified examples which results in a decision boundary with a smaller margin. This could give a good classification in the training set, as the accuracy of training set is increasing in the plot as $\lambda$ increases. However, due to the narrow margin in two classes, it is very sensitive to noise and to small changes in the independent variables (new data coming in). This is shown by the gradual decreasing accuracy on validation set for $\lambda > 20$.

2.2.2

To investigate the cosine of angle between to planes, we first write down the plane equations for each:

$$ \boldsymbol x \cdot w_1 + d_1 = 0 \quad \text{and} \quad \boldsymbol x \cdot w_2 + d_2 = 0 $$

The angle $\theta$ between the planes is defined as:

$$ cos(\theta) = |\frac{w_1 \cdot w_2}{|w_1||w_2|}| $$
In [ ]:
def train_svm_hyperplanes(X, y, lambdas):
    """
    Trains a Support Vector Machine (SVM) for different values of the regularization strength parameter and computes the cosine similarity
    between the resulting hyperplanes.

    :param X: feature set of the training data
    :param y: target set of the training data
    :param lambdas: list of regularization strengths to be used for training

    :return: a matrix of cosine similarities between the hyperplanes for different regularization strengths
    """
    n_lambdas = len(lambdas)
    cos_sims = np.zeros((n_lambdas, n_lambdas))

    for i, lambdai in enumerate(lambdas):
        wi = sgd(X, y, regul_strength=lambdai)
        wi = wi[:-1]

        # Compute cosine similarity between hyperplanes with the same lambda value
        cos_sims[i, i] = np.dot(wi, wi) / (np.linalg.norm(wi) * np.linalg.norm(wi))

        for j, lambdaj in enumerate(lambdas):
            if i < j:
                wj = sgd(X, y, regul_strength=lambdaj)
                wj = wj[:-1]
                cos_sim = np.dot(wi, wj) / (np.linalg.norm(wi) * np.linalg.norm(wj))
                cos_sims[i, j] = cos_sim
                cos_sims[j, i] = cos_sim

    return cos_sims

lambda_range = np.arange(1,50)
cos_sims = train_svm_hyperplanes(Xdb_train_aug, ydb_train, lambda_range)

The heatmap represents the cosine of the angle between two hyperplanes found using different regularization strengths $\lambda$. The angle between two hyperplanes is the angle between their normal vectors. The cosine of this angle ranges between -1 and 1, where -1 indicates that the two hyperplanes are parallel, 0 indicates that the two hyperplanes are perpendicular, and 1 indicates that the two hyperplanes are in the same direction. In general, a higher (absolute) cosine of the angle between two hyperplanes indicates that the two hyperplanes are more similar with each other, while a lower cosine of the angle between two hyperplanes indicates that the two hyperplanes are more dissimilar to each other.

First of all, all the diagonal blocks have cosine equals to 1, this is trivial as the angle between two parallel planes is of course zero.

From the color bar, we can see the largest difference in angle (equivalent to smallest cosine value) in our plot happens when one $\lambda$ is small, say from 1 to 5, and the other $\lambda$ is large from 5 to 50. This indicates two planes are quite different to each other. This because the small $\lambda$ allows more misclassification, yet large $\lambda$ narrows the margin between two classes. Two different tolerance will definitely gives us different hyper-plane for classification.

However, when two lambdas are both relatively larger, ie. both $\lambda > 5$, the angle between the two hyper-planes are quite similar. It can be seen that the right bottom corner shows cosine value around 1. It suggests that $\lambda \approx 5$ works kind of like a threshold, for $\lambda$ larger this threshold, the tolerance for misclassification and width of the margin is always similar. They all have similar hardness regardless the $\lambda$. Similarily, for the left upper block, where both lambdas are small, the softness of each pair is similar, giving similar hyper-plane.

2.2.4

In this section I train a soft margin kernelised SVM with loss function $$ L = \frac{1}{2} \mathbf{u}^{\mathrm{T}} \mathbf{K} \mathbf{u}+\lambda \sum_{i=1}^N \max \left\{0,1-y^{(i)}\left(\mathbf{K}^{(i)} \mathbf{u}+b\right)\right\} $$ with respect to $\mathrm{u}$ and $b$. The kernel is the sigmoid kernel: $$ [\mathbf{K}]_{i j} \equiv k\left(\mathbf{x}^{(i)}, \mathbf{x}^{(j)}\right)=\tanh \left(\sigma\left(\mathbf{x}^{(i)} \cdot \mathbf{x}^{(j)}\right)+1\right) $$

I defined the function to compute the kernel matrix as below.

In [ ]:
def sigmoid_kernel(X1, X2, sigma):
    """
    find the kernel matrix given data
    
    :param X1: (n1, m1) np array, each row corresponds to a data
    :param X2: (n2, m2) np array, each row corresponds to a data
    :param sigma: float, parameter of the Gaussian kernel
    
    :return kernel: (m, n) np array, the kernel matrix
        entry (i, j) is kernel between i'th data of X1 and j'th data of X2
    """
    kernel = np.tanh(sigma * (X1 @ X2.T) + 1)
    return kernel

Now in order to use stochastic gradient descent to train our SVM, we firstly have to calculate the derivative of L.

If the distance $1-y^{(i)}\left(\mathbf{K}^{(i)} \mathbf{u}+b\right) \leq 0$, then $L = \frac{1}{2} \mathbf{u}^{\mathrm{T}} \mathbf{K} \mathbf{u}$.

By lecture notes, $$ \frac{\partial L}{\partial \mathbf{u}} = \frac{1}{2} \cdot (\mathbf{K}+\mathbf{K}^T) \mathbf{u} = \frac{1}{2} \cdot 2\mathbf{K}\mathbf{u} = \mathbf{K}\mathbf{u} $$ where the second equality comes from the symmetry of $\mathbf{K}$ as $$[\mathbf{K}]_{i j} =\tanh \left(\sigma\left(\mathbf{x}^{(i)} \cdot \mathbf{x}^{(j)}\right)+1\right)=\tanh \left(\sigma\left(\mathbf{x}^{(j)} \cdot \mathbf{x}^{(i)}\right)+1\right) = [\mathbf{K}]_{j i}$$ where I use the fact that dot product of two vectors is a number.

If the distance is positive, we need to consider the pairwise derivative of the penalty as well, write $L' = \lambda(1-y^{(i)}\left(\mathbf{K}^{(i)} \mathbf{u}+b\right))$ $$ \frac{\partial}{\partial u^{(i)}}L' = -\lambda y^{(i)}\mathbf{K}^{(i)} \quad \text{and} \quad \frac{\partial}{\partial b}L' = -\lambda y^{(i)} $$

In [ ]:
def compute_cost_kernel(u, K, y, intercept, regul_strength=1e3):
    """
    Compute the hinge loss for Gaussian kernel

    :param u: (p+1,) numpy array, weights
    :parma K: (p+1, p+1) numpy array, the kernel matrix
    :param y: (n,) numpy array, the labels
    :param regul_strength: float, the parameter lambda, default 1e3
    :param intercept: the value of b in loss function

    :return (float): hinge loss
    """
    #Kernel trick
    distances = 1 - (y)*(K@u + intercept)
    distances[distances < 0] = 0  # equivalent to max(0, distance)
    hinge = regul_strength * distances.mean()

    # calculate cost
    return 0.5 * np.dot(u,K@u) + hinge

def calculate_cost_gradient_kernel(u, K_batch, y_batch, intercept, regul_strength=1e3):
    """
    Find the gradient of hinge loss w.r.t. w for a batch of K, y
    with Gaussian kernel used
    
    :param u: (D+1,) numpy array, weights in the larger space R^D
    :param K_batch: (k, D+1) np array, each row is a data
    :param y_batch: (k,) np array, labels of X_batch
    :param regul_strength: float, the parameter lambda, default 1e6
    
    :return gradient: (D+1,) np array, the average gradient of hinge loss among batches
    """
    # if only one example is passed
    if type(y_batch) == np.float64 or type(y_batch) == np.int64:
        y_batch = np.asarray([y_batch])
        K_batch = np.asarray([K_batch])  # gives multidimensional array
    
    distance = 1 - (y_batch * (K_batch @ u + intercept))
    #Keep the derivative of intercep together
    dw = np.zeros(len(u) + 1)

    # define the gradient with the hinge loss #
    for ind, d in enumerate(distance):
        if max(0, d)==0:
            di = np.zeros(len(u) + 1)
            #Derivative of first term, intercept is unchanged
            di[:-1] = K_batch @ u
        else:
            di = np.zeros(len(u) + 1)
            #Derivative of first term
            di[:-1] = K_batch @ u - (regul_strength * y_batch[ind] * K_batch[ind])
            #Derivative of intercept
            di[-1] = -regul_strength * y_batch[ind]
        dw += di

    return dw / len(y_batch)

Here is the function to perform stochastic gradient descent.

In [ ]:
def sgd_kernel(K, y, batch_size=32, max_iterations=4000, stop_criterion=0.001, learning_rate = 1e-3, regul_strength=1e3, print_outcome=False):
    """
    Perform stochastic gradient descent on hinge loss with Gaussian kernel
    
    :parma K: (D+1, D+1) numpy array, the kernel matrix
    :param y: (N,) numpy array, the labels
    :param batch_size: number of data points used for each iteration of SGD 
    :param max_iterations: int, maximum iterations allowed, default 4000
    :param stop_criterion: float, default 0.001,
        stop the algorithm when the percentage change in cost between two iterations < stop_criterion
    :param learning_rate: the parameter alpha multiplied to gradient, default 1e-4
    :param regul_strength: the parameter lambda, default 1e3
    :param print_outcome: boolean
        true: print 2^n th iteration cost for all n
        false: not print
    
    :return u: the solution obtained from SGD
    :return intercept: the solution b obtained from SGD
    """

    # initialise zero u and intercept
    u = np.zeros(K.shape[1])
    intercept = 0
    
    nth = 0
    # initialise starting cost as infinity
    prev_cost = np.inf
    
    # stochastic gradient descent
    indices = np.arange(len(y))
    for iteration in range(1, max_iterations):
        # shuffle to prevent repeating update cycles
        np.random.shuffle(indices)
        batch_idx = indices[:batch_size]
        K_b, y_b = K[batch_idx], y[batch_idx]
        for ki, yi in zip(K_b, y_b):
            #Derivative of u and intercept
            ascent = calculate_cost_gradient_kernel(u, ki, yi, intercept, regul_strength)
            #Learning rate decreases as interation goes on
            u -= learning_rate / iteration * ascent[:-1]
            intercept -= learning_rate / iteration * ascent[-1]
        
        # convergence check on 2^n'th iteration
        if iteration==2**nth or iteration==max_iterations-1:
            # compute cost
            cost = compute_cost_kernel(u, K, y, regul_strength = regul_strength, intercept = intercept)

            if print_outcome:
                print("Iteration is: {}, Cost is: {}".format(iteration, cost))
            # stop criterion
            if abs(prev_cost - cost) < stop_criterion * prev_cost:
                if iteration==2**nth:
                    #Notification of convergence only when iteration ends before max_iter
                    print('------iteration converged-------')
                return u, intercept
            
            prev_cost = cost
            nth += 1

    return u, intercept

Let us remind ourselves that

$$ \text{accuracy} = \frac{TP + TN}{N_{\text{validation}}} $$

It can be seen that linear SVM has a pretty good accuracy rate, which means it correctly labels 92.3% patients in our test dataset. The kernelised SVM performs slightly off compared to linear one in general. When $\sigma=0.01$, it performs the worst; while $\sigma=1$, it performs the best, even outperformed the linear SVM.

It worth noticing that when $\sigma=0.01$ and $\sigma=0.1$, the precision is NaN, which means zero positive has been labelled out. As a consequence, F-score is NaN (or zero). Accuracy is fully contributed from the true negatives.

However, $\sigma=1$ not only gives good accuracy, it results in a much higher f-score than linear SVM. This suggests than kernelised SVM can outperforms linear SVM when the $\sigma$ and $\lambda$ is well chosen. It suggests that our dataset distributed in a way which is not quite linearly separatabe, we need to use kernelised SVM to transform it into higher dimension to make it more distinguishable.

What my statistics is telling me is that our accuracy and precision is higher than F-score, our recall could be low. This means our SVM is wrongly allocated a significant amount of positive as negative. This could imporve by increasing the hardness of separation, reducing the margin, this could decrease the misdiagnosis of diabetic patients. But it comes with the risk of overfitting. Also we could try to increase the batch size in stochastic gradient descent, as larger batch size results better fitting, but it also comes with overfitting risk. Last but not least, we should investigate more into the influence of $\sigma$. My statistics shows me $\sigma =1$ seems to have quite good performance, this could also be optimised further by performing a grid search for $\sigma$ around 1.
